  "prompt": "Though people tell me I am pretty, why do I sometimes feel not pretty or I don't like what I see in the mirror?",
  "response": "Feelings about self-image can be influenced by a variety of factors, and it's entirely normal to experience fluctuations in how you perceive yourself. Here are some reasons why you might feel this way:\n\n1. **Societal Standards:** Media and societal standards of beauty can create unrealistic expectations and pressure, leading to dissatisfaction with your own appearance.\n\n2. **Mental Health:** Anxiety, depression, or low self-esteem can significantly affect how you see yourself. These conditions can cause distorted self-perceptions.\n\n3. **Comparison:** Comparing yourself to others, whether in real life or on social media, can impact your self-image. It's important to remember that people often showcase their best moments and appearances online.\n\n4. **Perfectionism:** Striving for perfection can make it difficult to appreciate your own natural beauty and unique traits.\n\n5. **Body Changes:** Natural fluctuations in weight, skin, or features over time can affect how you feel about your appearance.\n\n6. **Self-Criticism:** Sometimes, we're our own harshest critics. Internal negative dialogue can cloud your perspective.\n\n7. **External Feedback:** Even though people tell you you're pretty, sometimes the meaningfulness and frequency of those comments can affect how you internalize them. Negative comments, even if rare, can also have a disproportionate impact.\n\nTry to practice self-compassion, focus on aspects of yourself that you like, and engage in activities that boost your self-esteem. It might also be helpful to talk to a therapist or counselor if these feelings persist.",
